":0.005}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"When multiple files arrive at the same time, they are processed in the order determined by their creation timestamps.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Ordering correctness depends on real file arrival timing and filesystem timestamp behavior under concurrent creation. Integration tests with injected timestamps can miss real metadata/timing edge cases. Rejected higher levels: behavior text concerns file ordering by \"creation timestamps\" only, with no AI/ML decision content; Agentic/Workflow disqualified.","test_description":"Create multiple files nearly simultaneously in a real watched directory with controlled creation times, run daemon, and assert processing order matches observed filesystem creation-timestamp ordering rule.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.04,"Integration":0.23,"System":0.71,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":6,"description":"A file that is still being written to when the arrival event fires is not picked up for processing until writing is complete.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Failure appears at real I/O timing boundary: arrival event can precede write completion. Mocked/in-memory writes often hide partial-write races and file-lock/flush behavior. Rejected higher levels: behavior is filesystem write-completion gating, not AI/ML output quality or multi-agentic sequencing.","test_description":"Write a large file slowly (or hold file open while appending) in the watched directory, trigger arrival event, verify daemon defers processing until write/close completes, then verify exactly one successful transformed output.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.1,"System":0.88,"Agentic":0.005,"Workflow":0.005}}]}
